This is something I needed to patch in order to implement a feature in an application I'm working on.

Use case: Protect documents not owned by a user from deletion. Ownership info was stored in Weaviate metadata.

llama_index/vector_stores/weaviate.py:214: error: List item 0 has incompatible type "Dict[str, Sequence[str]]"; expected "str"  [list-item]

    def with_where(self, content: dict) -> "GetBuilder":

        Set `where` filter.

        Parameters
        ----------
        content : dict
            The content of the `where` filter to set. See examples below.

        Examples

        >>> content = {
        ...     'operator': '<operator>',
        ...     'operands': [
        ...         {
        ...             'path': [path],
        ...             'operator': '<operator>'
        ...             '<valueType>': <value>
        ...         },
        ...         {
        ...             'path': [<matchPath>],
        ...             'operator': '<operator>',

# Description

Adding the necessary abstractions and download capabilities for `LlamaDatasets`. If I may suggest starting with the notebooks to get a general sense of everything before diving into the code changes:

- `labelled-rag-datasets.ipynb`
- `downloading_llama_datasets.ipynb`
- `uploading_llama_datasets.ipynb`

NOTES:

1. This PR covers `LlamaDatasets` for one situation initially — more will be added to cover other scenarios in future PRs. This initial scenario is one where a data consumer wants to evaluate their own RAG pipeline on a Rag Datasaet. In particular, for their pipeline, they have their own way of creating an index, embeddings, and choice of generator LLM. So, to that end, we supply a `LabelledRagDataset` for them to use their RAG pipeline on to generate responses. 
2. I've proposed here a new abstraction `LabelledRagDataset` which can be seen as a refactor/enhancement of the `QueryResponseDataset`. A few reasons for this are:
    - The new abstraction I think its more natural and in-line with traditional machine learning datasets, represented by rows of examples (i.e., `LabelledRagDataExample`). So I think this might make it easier for ML/DL folks to pick up and run with.
    - The new abstraction stores information relevant to the task of evaluating RAG pipelines more directly and so I think leads to better UX
    - The name may be preferred over the former (this is not so strong of an argument)
(If we feel strongly to stick with `QueryResponseData` then that's okay too, I would just need to make some modifications).
3. Everything in download module points to my own fork/branch. Note also that for uploading and storing datasets I am proposing we use a new Github repo and configure it for LFS. For this draft, I am using a LFS repo on my own personal account.
